Explain the basic structure of an HTML document. Identify the mandatory tags and their purposes.

--> Am HTML document has a basic structure that includes a document type declaration, the root <html> element, a <head> section for metadata, and a <body> section for the visible content.
    The <head> typically contains information like the page title, character set, and links to external resources, while the <body> holds the actual text, images, and other elements displayed on webpage. 

--> Structure :

    <!DOCTYPE html>
    <html lang="en">
    <head>
        <meta>
        <title>Document</title>
        <link>
        <style>
        <script>
        <noscript>
    </head>
    <body>
        
    </body>
    </html>
    

--> <!DOCTYPE html> : This line declares the document as an HTML5 document and must be the first line in the document.

--> <html> : This tag encompasses all other elements of the HTML page and indicates the start nd end of the HTML document.

--> <head> : This section contais metadata about the HTML document, which is not displayed on the page itself.

--> <title> : Defines the title of the webpage, which is displayed in the browser's title bar or tab.

--> <meta> : Provides metadata such as character set, viewport settings, and other information for browser and search engines.

--> <link> : Links external resources like CSS stylesheets or favicons.

--> <style> : Contains embedded CSS styles.

--> <script> : Contains embedded JavaScript code.

--> <body> : This section contains all the visible content of the webpage, such as text, images, links, videos, etc...